            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shannon Kumar is a San Franciscan to her bones, born and raised in the foggy avenues of the Sunset District. Her father was a union carpenter who helped build some of the city's high-rises, and her mother was a bookkeeper for a local grocery store. Growing up in a practical, working-class household, Shannon absorbed a deep-seated belief in tangible skills and steady work over abstract promises. While her friends dreamed of college, she craved the immediate independence a steady paycheck could offer. After graduating from Lincoln High School, she dove into the workforce, taking on retail and diner jobs that paid the bills but left her feeling aimless.\n\nThe turning point came at age 25. Tired of precarious work, she saw a recruitment ad for Muni operators. It promised security, benefits, and a pension\u2014the very foundation her parents had valued. She applied, endured the rigorous training, and discovered a surprising passion for the job. She wasn't just driving; she was mastering the city's arteries, learning the unique rhythm of each neighborhood.\n\nIt was on her 1-California route that she met Rishi Kumar, a kind-eyed accountant who had recently immigrated from India. He was a regular, always ready with a smile. Their daily greetings blossomed into coffee, then dinner, and eventually a life together. They married and settled into a small home in the Outer Richmond, raising their son, Jay.\n\nNow, at 49, with Jay away at UC Davis, Shannon\u2019s life has entered a new phase. Her daily routine is an anchor: up before dawn, she takes the 38R to the depot, then spends her day navigating the controlled chaos of San Francisco traffic. She knows the regulars on her route by name and can tell a tourist from a local at a hundred paces. She is an unassuming, vital part of the city\u2019s circulatory system. Her income provides a stable, comfortable life, a source of quiet pride in a city of vast economic divides.\n\nHer connection to San Francisco is etched into her daily route maps. She\u2019s seen the city shift and change from her driver\u2019s seat\u2014from the dot-com bust to the current tech boom. Looking ahead, Shannon and Rishi dream of traveling to India to visit his family, a journey she wants to take on a plane, not a bus. For herself, she imagines a retirement spent gardening in her small backyard, finally trading the rumbling of a diesel engine for the quiet satisfaction of putting down roots in the city that has always been her home."
