            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 28, barely two years into her Muni career, when her father got on her 38 Geary bus. He sat near the front, silent, watching her handle the farebox, the stops, the traffic. When he got off at Park Presidio, he didn't say much. He just put a calloused carpenter\u2019s hand on her shoulder and gave a short, firm nod. In that one gesture, Shannon felt the immense weight of his approval. She hadn\u2019t gone to college, but she had secured a life of tangible worth, a union job he understood and respected.\n\n2.\nRishi was just a regular on her 1-California route until the day he missed his stop. They were caught in a brief, easy conversation about the weather when he suddenly looked up, startled, as the bus pulled away from his corner. They both broke into laughter\u2014a shared, unscripted moment of surprise. It was the first time she saw him not as a passenger, but as a person. That laugh, echoing in the cavern of the bus, was the gentle jolt that knocked their two separate tracks onto a single, shared line.\n\n3.\nJay was four, sitting in the priority seat right behind her as she drove. He was a small, serious observer, his eyes wide as he watched his mother command the huge vehicle. She remembers glancing in the rearview mirror and seeing him quietly mimicking the *psssht* of the air brakes and the *ding* of the stop request bell. In that moment, her job wasn't just a paycheck; it was the powerful, rumbling engine that was carrying her son\u2019s future forward. The pride she felt was fierce, protective, and deeply satisfying.\n\n4.\nThe quietest bus ride of her life was the night after they dropped Jay at UC Davis for his freshman year. It was late, her shift over, and as she took the 38R home, the familiar seats felt impossibly empty. The dependable rhythm of the route, usually a comfort, now seemed to just mark the growing distance between her and her son. Gazing out at the blurred city lights, she felt the distinct, aching shift from one phase of life to the next, realizing the road ahead was suddenly, quietly, wide open for her and Rishi.\n\n5.\nHer most cherished view isn\u2019t on a postcard. It\u2019s a recurring gift from the city, granted on early morning runs. Cresting a hill in the Richmond, the fog is often so thick it swallows the world. But sometimes, for just a moment, she\u2019ll see the two red towers of the Golden Gate Bridge floating untethered above the sea of white mist. It\u2019s a private, fleeting spectacle. In those moments, she feels a profound connection to San Francisco\u2014a secret shared between her and the city she navigates every day."
